mi Wood</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG00305X%2F1"><gtr:id>60BB8115-EDC5-4D08-9D6D-334D3116337F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Cultures of Urban Surveillance: Assessing the Intensity and Character of Surveillance in Global Cities.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G00305X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This Fellowship will examine the globalisation of 'risk-surveillance society', its policies, practices and socio-technical systems, and how this globalization is mediated or moderated in different global cities with varied cultural expectations and social norms.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The Fellowship has three broad themes:
&lt;br />
&lt;br />
&lt;ol>
 &lt;li>The extent of surveillance. How much surveillance is there? What are the forms of surveillance? How far do they extend and how deep do they go?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>The political economy of surveillance. How do surveillance markets, technologies, policy and politics interact in these cities? What is the relative strength of globalizing forces (dominant security and economic orientations) and national or local forces? How can this help guide policy and action?&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>The understanding of surveillance. How do individuals and groups form their conceptions of surveillance? How important is it to them? How do these conceptions and ethics vary in different societies and cultures? Can this help us develop new ethical forms of, or responses to, surveillance?&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>
&lt;br />The Fellowship will revolve around four identically-organised comparative case-studies of London, Rio de Janeiro, Tokyo and Toronto, working with partner organisations in each.
